    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>Imaging the 61 Vir debris disk</prj:name>
        <prj:note>The primary goal of the proposed observation is to image continuum emission from the 61 Vir debris disk. In our most radially extended model, the disk is ~7" in angular size. An angular resolution of 1.08" and a continuum sensitivity of 17 microJy/beam will be necessary to ensure differentiation between the different planetary system scenarios, and will detect the faintest component envisaged in the different scenarios (50 microJy/beam) at a signal to noise of 3. The required continuum sensitivity drives our time request, which consists of 2.8hr on-source, and 6.0hr including overheads. Additionally, we aim to search for CO J=3-2 line emission within the disk. Taking into account our continuum constraints, we will obtain a line sensitivity of 1.4 mJy/beam per spectral channel, which will enable us to probe very low (~10^-8 Mearth) CO mass levels in the 61 Vir system. The spectral resolution (~1.7 km/s) will be adequate to resolve the Keplerian spread in velocities (~10 km/s) that is expected from CO gas within the disk.</prj:note>
